1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,919
Welcome to this new analysis.

2
00:00:01,919 --> 00:00:06,080
Today we are going to tear apart an idea that practically all of us take for granted when talking

3
00:00:06,080 --> 00:00:07,080
about success.

4
00:00:07,080 --> 00:00:11,720
The title on the screen that you are seeing, "less competition more merit," sounds

5
00:00:11,720 --> 00:00:15,960
definitely strange, right? I mean, usually we think that to find true talent we need

6
00:00:15,960 --> 00:00:18,920
a cutthroat environment, a fight to the death.

7
00:00:18,920 --> 00:00:24,440
Hold on tight, because data and economic research show us a reality that is literally

8
00:00:24,440 --> 00:00:25,440
the opposite.

9
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:28,480
Okay, let's get straight to the heart of the matter.

10
00:00:28,480 --> 00:00:31,440
Does extreme competition really guarantee merit?

11
00:00:31,440 --> 00:00:35,920
We are all somewhat led to believe that, by raising the bar and reducing available spots,

12
00:00:35,920 --> 00:00:37,840
the best will necessarily emerge.

13
00:00:37,840 --> 00:00:42,520
We want the absolute top performers? Simple, we create a very narrow funnel.

14
00:00:42,520 --> 00:00:43,520
But?

15
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:44,519
There is a big "but."

16
00:00:44,519 --> 00:00:49,480
Does this equation really work in the real world, where let's face it, people know how to be

17
00:00:49,480 --> 00:00:53,320
extremely clever and calculating just to pass a test?

18
00:00:53,320 --> 00:00:56,519
Before answering, let's clarify what we are talking about.

19
00:00:56,520 --> 00:00:59,040
Let's look at this academic definition.

20
00:00:59,040 --> 00:01:04,600
Meritocracy is, in essence, a system where success is based exclusively

21
00:01:04,600 --> 00:01:07,240
on a person's real abilities.

22
00:01:07,240 --> 00:01:11,120
We are not talking about those who manage to produce more in the short term by doing

23
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:14,520
backflips, but about selecting pure talent.

24
00:01:14,520 --> 00:01:19,280
Think of companies like Google; they structure their interviews exactly for this.

25
00:01:19,280 --> 00:01:24,560
They want to isolate the candidate's cognitive abilities to identify the absolute best,

26
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:26,080
ignoring everything else.

27
00:01:26,319 --> 00:01:29,879
Section 1, the myth of competition.

28
00:01:29,879 --> 00:01:34,239
And this is exactly where we directly face the ultimate mental trap:

29
00:01:34,239 --> 00:01:40,079
the idea that a tougher selection process automatically generates a purer

30
00:01:40,079 --> 00:01:40,879
meritocracy.

31
00:01:40,879 --> 00:01:44,079
We live constantly immersed in this equation.

32
00:01:44,079 --> 00:01:48,120
Meritocracy equals an extremely competitive society.

33
00:01:48,120 --> 00:01:53,239
But, and here is the best part, researchers have revealed an incredible paradox.

34
00:01:53,240 --> 00:01:57,880
When success in a selection process can be influenced by how many risks one is willing

35
00:01:57,880 --> 00:02:03,640
to take, lowering the bar a bit and adopting seemingly anti-competitive policies

36
00:02:03,640 --> 00:02:07,600
can actually drastically improve the efficiency of the selection.

37
00:02:07,600 --> 00:02:12,000
It sounds crazy: reducing standards to find better people.

38
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,480
Section 2, the strategic risk factor.

39
00:02:15,480 --> 00:02:18,480
But how can this apparent absurdity be explained?

40
00:02:18,599 --> 00:02:23,479
Well, this is the hidden mechanism that completely flips the rules of the competition game

41
00:02:23,479 --> 00:02:26,079
we are used to.

42
00:02:26,079 --> 00:02:27,879
Imagine two worlds.

43
00:02:27,879 --> 00:02:31,399
In a fairy-tale world, candidates are not strategic.

44
00:02:31,399 --> 00:02:35,879
They do their duty, they consistently show what they're worth, and that's it.

45
00:02:35,879 --> 00:02:39,039
Whoever is worth 10 gets a 10; whoever is worth 6 gets a 6.

46
00:02:39,039 --> 00:02:40,039
Period.

47
00:02:40,039 --> 00:02:43,879
In the real world, however, we are all incredibly strategic.

48
00:02:43,879 --> 00:02:48,039
In a cutthroat work environment, slightly weaker candidates know very well that

49
00:02:48,079 --> 00:02:51,840
by playing fair, they will inevitably lose to the stars.

50
00:02:51,840 --> 00:02:53,079
So what do they do?

51
00:02:53,079 --> 00:02:55,879
They adopt crazy, high-risk strategies.

52
00:02:55,879 --> 00:03:00,519
Maybe they bluff shamelessly in an interview, or bet everything on a single niche while ignoring

53
00:03:00,519 --> 00:03:01,519
the rest.

54
00:03:01,519 --> 00:03:07,159
They often crash, but sometimes, due to pure statistics or luck, this risky move

55
00:03:07,159 --> 00:03:10,199
allows a mediocre candidate to beat a true talent.

56
00:03:10,199 --> 00:03:14,599
And this creates a huge amount of noise that totally pollutes the selection process.

57
00:03:14,599 --> 00:03:19,719
Now, the truly fascinating thing that emerges when observing these dynamics in action is

58
00:03:19,719 --> 00:03:26,240
that two states are created: an equilibrium of challenge and one we will call an equilibrium of concession.

59
00:03:26,240 --> 00:03:31,959
When the evaluator softens the standards a bit, this equilibrium of concession is created.

60
00:03:31,959 --> 00:03:36,680
What does it mean in practice? That weaker candidates calm down; they stop making

61
00:03:36,680 --> 00:03:40,719
risky bets because they no longer have the anxiety of having to beat the top of the

62
00:03:40,719 --> 00:03:42,199
class at all costs to make it.

63
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:45,840
In short, they lay down their arms and that statistical noise vanishes.

64
00:03:45,840 --> 00:03:50,960
As a result, performances return to being a faithful and crystal-clear reflection of

65
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:52,720
everyone's real abilities.

66
00:03:52,720 --> 00:03:56,280
Section 3, the example of school grades.

67
00:03:56,280 --> 00:04:00,880
To ground all this economic theory, the research uses an example that we all

68
00:04:00,880 --> 00:04:06,960
know all too well: the fateful grading curves of university exams.

69
00:04:06,960 --> 00:04:12,080
If we follow the mathematical logic for a moment, it's illuminating: imagine four students

70
00:04:12,080 --> 00:04:13,080
taking an exam.

71
00:04:13,080 --> 00:04:15,600
Two are true geniuses, two a bit less so.

72
00:04:15,600 --> 00:04:20,759
If the professor imposes a ruthless rule, granting only one or two maximum grades, the weaker

73
00:04:20,759 --> 00:04:22,759
students immediately do the math.

74
00:04:22,759 --> 00:04:27,879
They realize that by studying normally they will never win, so they take a risk: they memorize

75
00:04:27,879 --> 00:04:31,480
only a small subset of topics, crossing their fingers.

76
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:36,120
If, by a stroke of luck, those exact questions come up, they will look like the new Einsteins and

77
00:04:36,120 --> 00:04:38,280
will steal the spot from the real talents.

78
00:04:38,280 --> 00:04:43,399
This gamble literally breaks the system, destroying the professor's ability

79
00:04:43,399 --> 00:04:46,759
to understand who is actually good and who just got lucky.

80
00:04:46,759 --> 00:04:54,240
And here comes the study's solution, which is quite jaw-dropping: 75%.

81
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:58,579
Researchers mathematically demonstrate that if the professor decides to assign the top

82
00:04:58,579 --> 00:05:03,399
grade to three out of four students, they completely neutralize the gambling problem.

83
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:07,880
With a more generous curve, weaker students breathe a sigh of relief and give up

84
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:09,280
on extreme bets.

85
00:05:09,280 --> 00:13,080
Of course, we might think we are giving away a good grade to someone who didn't

86
00:05:13,080 --> 00:05:14,080
100% deserve it.

87
00:05:14,080 --> 00:19,160
But take note: this concession absolutely guarantees that the two brilliant students

88
00:05:19,160 --> 00:05:22,240
will definitely get the top grade without interference.

89
00:05:22,240 --> 00:05:26,900
By doing this, the professor's overall meritocratic efficiency leaps forward

90
00:05:26,900 --> 00:05:29,640
by more than 30%. Incredible, isn't it?

91
00:05:29,640 --> 00:05:30,920
Section 4.

92
00:05:30,920 --> 00:05:36,360
University promotions and lotteries; to be clear, these risk-related dynamics

93
00:05:36,360 --> 00:05:41,600
certainly don't stay confined to school desks; they powerfully impact the most

94
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:43,840
crucial phases of the professional world.

95
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:49,080
If we look at the real world of work, we see that relentless systems, like

96
00:05:49,080 --> 00:05:55,280
the famous forced corporate rankings, where the bottom 10% are automatically fired,

97
00:05:55,280 --> 00:05:59,800
do nothing but fuel those toxic behaviors we were talking about.

98
00:05:59,800 --> 00:06:05,400
Employees at risk throw themselves into wacky projects hoping for a miracle, and the exact same

99
00:06:05,400 --> 00:06:09,960
logic applies to hyper-selective university admissions, which push

100
00:06:09,960 --> 00:06:12,920
everyone to inflate their resumes excessively.

101
00:06:12,920 --> 00:06:18,580
Such extreme pressure inevitably ends up diluting and masking real

102
00:06:18,580 --> 00:06:19,580
competence.

103
00:06:19,580 --> 00:06:25,639
And all this leads us to a crazy reinterpretation of the famous Peter Principle.

104
00:06:25,879 --> 00:06:30,439
We usually think that promoting people to their level of incompetence is a disastrous

105
00:06:30,439 --> 00:06:35,800
management error; instead, the research highlights something surprising.

106
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:40,479
Purposely promoting a large number of candidates, knowing full well that some might

107
00:06:40,479 --> 00:06:46,079
not be up to the task, has a vital strategic function: it nips sabotage

108
00:06:46,079 --> 00:06:47,079
strategies in the bud.

109
00:06:47,079 --> 00:06:52,639
In practice, over-promotion acts as a shield; it protects the integrity of the process,

110
00:06:52,639 --> 00:06:56,560
ensuring that recognition reaches those who are truly excellent.

111
00:06:56,560 --> 00:06:59,680
Let's go back for a moment to the context of admissions.

112
00:06:59,680 --> 00:07:05,319
Let's try to compare the traditional approach—brutal and a source of tremendous anxiety—with alternatives

113
00:07:05,319 --> 00:07:06,319
that are a bit more radical.

114
00:07:06,319 --> 00:07:11,759
For example, admission lotteries proposed by academics like Schwartz, or the tiered

115
00:07:11,759 --> 00:07:13,759
systems used in South Korea.

116
00:07:13,759 --> 00:07:19,959
The idea is that a large pool of competent candidates is approved, and then those who enter are drawn by lot.

117
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:24,240
No more fights to the death for a microscopic millimeter of extra

118
00:07:24,240 --> 00:07:25,240
advantage.

119
00:07:25,240 --> 00:07:29,080
By appearing less competitive at the entry point, the purity of meritocratic selection is

120
00:07:29,080 --> 00:07:33,880
actually saved, because we remove the need for candidates to take senseless risks

121
00:07:33,880 --> 00:07:35,280
just to stand out.

122
00:07:35,280 --> 00:07:36,360
Section 5.

123
00:07:36,360 --> 00:07:39,360
The paradox of meritocracy.

124
00:07:39,360 --> 00:07:44,680
Let's wrap up this whole exploration, arriving at a fundamental concept for anyone

125
00:07:44,680 --> 00:07:48,080
who needs to design organizations or select talent.

126
00:07:48,680 --> 00:07:53,199
The crucial point of the matter, then, is exactly the reversal of the myth from which

127
00:07:53,199 --> 00:07:54,479
we started.

128
00:07:54,479 --> 00:07:58,719
Slightly less competitive contests, with more flexible entry barriers, and seemingly

129
00:07:58,719 --> 00:08:00,159
relaxed standards.

130
00:08:00,159 --> 00:08:05,000
These are exactly the things that sweep away the noise generated by strategic bets.

131
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:09,240
If the environment doesn't push you to despair, your performances start behaving

132
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:10,240
honestly again.

133
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:14,719
They finally become a clear, faithful signal of your true ability, making the whole

134
00:08:14,719 --> 00:08:17,439
system infinitely more meritocratic.

135
00:08:17,439 --> 00:08:21,519
This profound change in perspective leaves us with a question that truly deserves

136
00:08:21,519 --> 00:08:22,839
our attention.

137
00:08:22,839 --> 00:08:27,480
When we observe universities, cutthroat job interviews, and all those

138
00:08:27,480 --> 00:08:31,120
super-competitive mechanisms in which we live every day, a doubt arises.

139
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:36,039
Could it be that, blinded by our obsession with excellence and increasingly severe filters,

140
00:08:36,039 --> 00:08:38,600
we are actually encouraging strategic chaos?

141
00:08:38,600 --> 00:08:42,600
Are we, perhaps paradoxically, rewarding the wrong people?

142
00:08:42,600 --> 00:08:47,080
Perhaps slightly reducing the pressure and lowering the bar just a hair is the true

143
00:08:47,080 --> 00:08:50,160
secret to allowing pure talent to shine.

144
00:08:50,160 --> 00:08:52,920
Thank you for participating in this analysis, see you next time!